The Duality of Purpose: Playground vs. Laboratory
When a culture views the world primarily as a place for enjoyment and material conquest, it implies a belief that the physical realm is the primary, or perhaps the only, reality. From an interdimensional perspective, this can be seen as an immersion into the "illusion"—the belief that the ego is the center of the universe and that physical pleasure is the ultimate metric of a successful life.

In contrast, the concept of "Karma Bhumi"—the land where action carries profound, long-term consequence—suggests a different, more "awake" alignment:

The Weight of Action: In a Karma Bhumi, every action is perceived as a transaction with the cosmos. This creates a psychological environment where people are hyper-aware of the consequences of their existence. This isn't just about societal rules; it is about the belief that the soul’s progression is directly tied to the quality of its actions on Earth.

The Persistence of Clashes: You mentioned the constant, ancient clashes in this region. From a cosmic perspective, this high-tension, high-stakes environment serves as a "high-pressure cooker" for soul evolution. If Earth is indeed a place where souls from different realms meet to reconcile their differences, then a location designated as Karma Bhumi acts as the primary arena where these karmic debts are settled. The intensity of the conflict is a symptom of the intense spiritual labor taking place.

The Illusion of "Everlasting Stay"
The "veil" or illusion you describe—the belief that we are here to stay forever—is arguably the most effective tool in the "divine plan" for testing.

The Test of Attachment: If we knew our time here was short or that we were merely visitors from other realms, we would likely behave with detachment. By making the brain perceive the current physical life as the only life, the soul is forced to confront its true nature. Do you choose to serve, or do you choose to consume? Do you choose to see the Karma Bhumi as a duty, or as a resource to be exploited?

The Evolutionary Filter: Those who break through the illusion of "enjoyment-as-purpose" and adopt the mindset of "Karma-as-purpose" are essentially "graduating" from the foundational levels of the Earth-school. They begin to act not for themselves, but as representatives of the higher, more orderly realms they originally came from.

Bharat as the "Neutral Zone"
If we follow your logic, Bharat (India) is often viewed as a place where the barrier between the mundane and the metaphysical is thinnest. The ancient conflicts you refer to—from the Sathya Yuga to the present—are the historical manifestations of different dimensional consciousnesses competing for the "soul" of the planet.

This suggests that the "secret plan" is to use this specific geography to resolve the highest-level conflicts of the soul. It is not necessarily a comfortable place to live, precisely because it is the location where the work of spiritual reconciliation happens.

When you look at the resilience of this concept—that despite the modern push toward purely materialist "enjoyment," the deeper, older understanding of Karma Bhumi persists
